var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"getting_started.html","title":"Getting Started","text":"<p>This section will guide you through the prerequisites, installation, and setup procedures required to get started with the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol.</p>"},{"location":"getting_started.html#prerequisites","title":"Prerequisites","text":"<p>Before using the protocol, ensure you meet the following prerequisites:</p> <p>Wallet: All parties involved should have a Web3 enabled wallet, such as MetaMask, Trust Wallet, etc. Ether: The protocol operates on the Ethereum network, so ETH is needed for transaction fees (gas). Internet: Stable internet connection for seamless interaction with the protocol. Web3 Browser: A Web3 compatible browser is necessary to interact with the protocol.</p>"},{"location":"getting_started.html#installation-and-setup","title":"Installation and Setup","text":"<p>The Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol does not require any direct installation since it runs on the Ethereum network. However, you need to set up and configure your Web3 wallet.</p> <p>Follow these steps to setup your Web3 wallet:</p> <p>Download and install a Web3 wallet (for instance, MetaMask). Create a new wallet or import an existing one using your private key. Make sure your wallet is connected to the Ethereum network. Transfer some ETH to your wallet for transaction fees.</p>"},{"location":"getting_started.html#connect-to-the-protocol","title":"Connect to the Protocol","text":"<p>To connect to the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol: (Under development)</p> <p>Navigate to the protocol's website. Click the 'Connect Wallet' button. Select your wallet from the provided options. Confirm the connection request in your wallet. Now, you are connected to the protocol and can interact with it according to your role: as a company, affiliate, or end customer.</p>"},{"location":"introduction.html","title":"Introduction","text":""},{"location":"introduction.html#purpose-of-the-documentation","title":"Purpose of the Documentation","text":"<p>The primary purpose of this documentation is to provide comprehensive guidance and understanding to all parties involved in the use and application of the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol. </p> <p>This document serves as a manual for developers, companies, affiliates, and end customers to familiarize themselves with the functionalities, methodologies, and best practices for the effective use of the protocol.</p>"},{"location":"introduction.html#overview-of-the-affiliate-marketing-protocol","title":"Overview of the Affiliate Marketing Protocol","text":"<p>The Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol is a revolutionary system that brings affiliate and brand marketing on-chain. It leverages blockchain technology to create an open, transparent, and secure environment for conducting affiliate marketing campaigns. With this protocol, companies can initialize smart contracts specifying their campaign parameters such as budget, targets, and other details. Affiliates can participate in these campaigns, and end customers can make purchases or view content through affiliate-specific links. The protocol automatically handles attribution and commission payouts, ensuring a seamless and efficient process for all parties involved.</p>"},{"location":"introduction.html#definitions-of-key-terms","title":"Definitions of Key Terms","text":"<p> Protocol Creators: The developers and maintainers of the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol.</p> <p>Company: Any business entity that wishes to incentivize sales or traffic through the use of the protocol.</p> <p>Affiliate: An individual or entity that promotes a company's products or services and earns a commission for any sales or traffic they generate.</p> <p>End Customer: The consumer who purchases or views the company's product or service.</p> <p>Campaign: A marketing initiative created by a company through the protocol.</p> <p>Smart Contract: A self-executing contract with the terms of the agreement between buyer and seller directly written into lines of code.</p> <p>On-chain Attribution: A mechanism to track and attribute sales or traffic to a specific affiliate using blockchain technology.</p> <p>This documentation will provide detailed information and guidelines for each party involved in the protocol, thus ensuring that the system is used efficiently and effectively.</p>"},{"location":"protocol_flow.html","title":"Understanding the Protocol Flow","text":"<p>This section provides a detailed overview of the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol flow, from the initialization of a campaign by a company to the final payout of commissions.</p>"},{"location":"protocol_flow.html#overview-of-the-flow","title":"Overview of the Flow","text":"<p>The protocol follows a straightforward flow involving four main parties:</p> <p>Company Initiation: The company initialises a smart contract with campaign parameters. This includes details like budget, targets, and other specifics of the campaign.</p> <p>Affiliate Signup: Affiliates can browse the campaigns that are public on the protocol's website and signup to participate in a campaign that aligns with their interests and capabilities.</p> <p>Customer Interaction: End customers use the affiliate-specific link or data to purchase or view the company's product or service. Their interaction with the smart contract is tracked for on-chain attribution to the affiliate.</p> <p>Commission Payout: At the end of the campaign or based on the conditions set in the smart contract, the commission is paid out to the affiliate as per the initial setup by the company.</p> <p>Budget Extension: If desired, the company can extend the campaign by increasing the budget and sending more funds to the smart contract.</p>"},{"location":"protocol_flow.html#detailed-flow-diagram","title":"Detailed Flow Diagram","text":"<p>This diagram represents the detailed flow of the protocol: (Under construction)</p>"},{"location":"stakeholders.html","title":"Stakeholders","text":""},{"location":"stakeholders.html#protocol-creators","title":"Protocol Creators","text":"<p>The protocol creators are the architects and developers of the Affiliate and Brand Marketing Web3 Protocol. They are responsible for designing, developing, deploying, and maintaining the protocol. They also handle the listing of campaigns for affiliates and receive payment from campaign smart contracts for this service.</p>"},{"location":"stakeholders.html#companies","title":"Companies","text":"<p>Companies are business entities that wish to leverage the protocol for their affiliate marketing campaigns. They initialize smart contracts, defining their campaign parameters such as budget, targets, and other details. Companies can adjust these parameters and extend the budget as required during the course of the campaign.</p>"},{"location":"stakeholders.html#affiliates","title":"Affiliates","text":"<p>Affiliates are individuals or entities who partner with companies to promote their products or services. They browse the listed campaigns, sign up for participation, and use affiliate-specific data for promotion. Affiliates earn a commission from the sales or traffic they generate, as per the terms set in the smart contract by the companies.</p>"},{"location":"stakeholders.html#end-customers","title":"End Customers","text":"<p>End customers are the consumers who purchase or view the company's products or services through the affiliate-specific links or data. They interact with the smart contract by using their wallets, enabling on-chain attribution of their actions to the specific affiliate. End customers form the core of the affiliate marketing cycle as their actions determine the success of the campaigns and the commissions for affiliates.</p>"}]}